WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Okay, good morning. Today is Sunday, December 13th, 2015. This is David Klein from Virginia Tech, and working with the Southern oral history program at UNC Chapel Hill, also with the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Today we have the honor of being with Mr. Dion Diamond, who I will ask to introduce himself in just a moment. We have the camera today.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:46.000
We have John Bishop from Media Generation. We also have with us today Gouha Shankar from the Library of Congress.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:54.000
So Mr. Diamond, I just would like to say good morning, and thank you very much for being part of this project, and if you could just introduce yourself, but I appreciate it.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Good morning. I'm Dion Diamond, and I thank you for having me as a part of the project. I look forward to seeing you outcome.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Wonderful. Thank you. So I'd like to start just by we're obviously going to talk about your involvement in the Civil Rights Movement, but I want to start with your childhood, and if you could just tell us a little bit about where and when you are raised, and I'll ask you a few questions about your family, the kind of influences that you may have seen as you got.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
More involved in in the movement itself.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Okay, let's try this one. I'm originally from Petersburg, Virginia. The first 18 years spent in Petersburg, a totally segregated community, segregated high school, and our interest school, and even the state college there was essentially all black.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
At least I don't even know now whether or not it was black, Negro or Colott, we've come through so many iterations.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
At any rate.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Petersburg, as I said, was truly a segregated town. And as I grew up, I don't know how I really got involved, but I was involved in sit-ins before sit-ins became a named item.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:16.000
I would go into the local five-in-dime store and see the Colott water fountain and the white water fountain.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
I would see the lunch counter that I wasn't allowed to sit at, which I did.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And of course, when the waitress of the counterperson spoke to me and said, you know, we can't serve you, I would continue to sit.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
And then she would call the manager. The manager would come over and I would still sit.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And then she would call the police. That's what I left. So my sit-ins were very haphazard, spontaneous, and the local library.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:57.000
There was a color entrance at the rear. And we were allowed to go into the stacks. And of course, I would go into the color entrance, but I would venture into the stacks.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:03.000
And at any rate, I just thought it kind of crazy that I should grow up in an environment like that.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:12.000
I don't know where that influence came from because there was no integrated activity that I could look at in Petersburg and know it.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:26.000
There was anything about it. I think when I was 16, I went to a town called Monticello, New York to work supposedly in a laundry.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:38.000
And the cat skills and that's what they formally call the Jewish apps. And all of these big hotels would send their laundry to a laundry-cleaning facility.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:44.000
And I went at 816, well, soon to turn 17, but supposedly to work at the laundry.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
There were many kids from my town went there and that's how I found out about it.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And they had no work available at the laundry. I'm walking down the street and here's this restaurant. The name of it was the Frontier.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:05.000
They were putting the finishing touches on it. It had an open and it said, help warn it.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:14.000
I walked in and said, hey, look, I've had experience as a short-order cook. And if you need, you know, a short-order cook, I'd like for you to consider me.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And you have references. And of course, I said, yes, I'm lying to my teeth because I had no previous experience out of the cooking-my-famous kitchen.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:32.000
I ran to the nearest payfold, called Why Aren't in New Brunswick, New Jersey. Her name was Janet Morgan.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:44.000
I said, hey, if someone calls you and asks, you know, if I cooked in your restaurant and you own Morgan's restaurant now, so I fabricated my experience.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Anyway, I got the job. I think it was about a month later, the guy said, you know, I figured out soon after you started working that you didn't know a dog thing about being a short-order cook, but you picked it up so quickly, that was it.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:05.000
But that experience in Monticello was my first exposure to persons who were white.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Because again, Petersburg totally segregated. Monticello, rather an integrated community, both religiously and color-wise.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:26.000
I started Howard University in September of 1959.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:31.000
I was a physics major.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Shortly after that, when Snick was founded in the city and started in Greensboro, we at Howard supposedly, the pit of me, the capstone in Black education, were doing nothing because DC proper was not legally, or by law, segregated, even though in fact, you know, it certainly was.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Let me interrupt you just for a second. So you said you have this kind of got reaction against the segregation that you had grown up with in your town.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:22.000
Did you ever talk about it with your peers or with your family? And then when you got to Howard, was that something that, you know, even though nothing was happening immediately there, was that something that was discussed?

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:31.000
No, it was not discussed until the city and started in Greensboro. And that's when we started talking about it because what are we doing about it?

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:39.000
And as you can imagine back then, if you crossed Potomac River into Virginia, you've got segregation.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:48.000
If you crossed the imaginary line, or the district line into Maryland, western avenue, or eastern avenue, you've got segregation.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And we said, we've got to do something here in DC at Howard. So we organized this group called the Nonviolent Action Group.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:09.000
And we went over to Virginia to the segregated drug fair, drug chain, lunch counter, and had our first city, and this is after, of course, North Carolina.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:14.000
So do you remember first reading about the Greensboro, very first?

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:15.000
Yes.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:21.000
And I said, well, again, nothing in DC we can do, even though believe it or not.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:30.000
Back then, they didn't even want, you could go into the most expensive min shop, and they didn't want you to try on the clothing.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So that was a kind of a bitter thing, you could have had the money to purchase, but they did not want you to, I guess, so all their clothing.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:54.000
But again, off first city was at the, the cherry deal, I'm going to say the drug fair in cherry deal over in Alexandria.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:03.000
We desegregated that entire area within two weeks. And I don't know if you've seen it, but there's this picture.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:08.000
In fact, it's in the closet.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:19.000
George Lincoln Rockwell of the American Nazi party came in and surrounded us as we had to sit in. And it was just amazing.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:26.000
I'm surprised that I didn't panic. It's amazing when you're young and reckless.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:34.000
I call it the eupholic zuberance because I must admit we were in some dangerous situations.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:41.000
And it never occurred that day. It says dangerous as it is. Oh, why is it?

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:49.000
So I've seen the pictures. Your calmness emanates out of these pictures. And I needed to ask you about that.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:53.000
As I look at that picture today, I'm surprised.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:09:10.000
You know, I may be getting ahead of myself, but there's this big debate that there was this big debate and probably still is as to whether or not violence is a philosophy or whether or not it's a tactic or whether or not it's an expansion of religion.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:20.000
I'll let you know well into this one. I believe nonviolence as a tactic.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:26.000
I don't believe it in it as a philosophy.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:33.000
My reasoning is the police and the army have the guns and the ammunition that we had nothing.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:47.000
So we're good with it to be somewhat violent. But off camera and off the sit-ins, hey, if you're back me, I'm going to try to lose my shoe up your head.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:57.000
So I truly believe in it as a tactic and several of the people whom I get presentations with indeed believe it as a way of life.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:10.000
And I whenever that there are three of us who usually combine to give these presentations and almost immediately one of us will say, well, I like my two fellow freedom writers.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:22.000
I believe it as every way of life and then someone else would say, well, one is a minister. He believes it as a philosophy and a religious path.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:31.000
But at any rate, after that desegregation within two weeks in Virginia, we said, well, what else can we do?

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:37.000
There was this amusement park right across the Maryland line called Glennaco.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:48.000
And they used to bus white kids from the city to this amusement park. But people of color could not utilize the facilities.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:54.000
Well, it wasn't as if we could have a sit-in inside the park because we couldn't get in.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:08.000
So we put up a picket line around the outside of the park. And I think for that entire summer, for the balance of that summer, we just picket it.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:09.000
The people who live in...

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:10.000
This is the summer of 1960?

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:11.000
Yes.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
That's it. The summer of 1960.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:33.000
I think the most outstanding memory I have of that is the people in Glennaco, which is mostly a Jewish community, which had covenants that you could not sell your house to...

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.000
Well, you know what I'm saying.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:41.000
What I found the most interesting aspect of that was I put on...

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:52.000
I don't know if you'd call it a Gashiki, but a traditional gown worn by persons from Africa.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:58.000
And including whatever the headband is called.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:18.000
One of the... How about the name of Hyman Bookbag, if I recall correctly, who was a high up in the labor movement, arranged for this big long black limousine and a white uniformed chauffeur and a white female interpreter?

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:24.000
I'm sitting at the back of the limousine, wearing this African gobb with my interpreter.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
We pull up in front of Glennaco.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
The show gets out, opens the door.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.000
I step out.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
And in my pigeon...

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
Fitch.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
I'm trying to walk into the park and I said,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
J2Z, open the park, meet no!

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
And I thought I was saying I wish to enter the park right now.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And I hope that's how it came out.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:53.000
But anyway, this security guard who had to be at least 65 years of age and frail.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
I mean, he...

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:58.000
I mean, they were charged if it was him.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:04.000
But that entire summer we picketed Glennaco.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:11.000
And the following year when schools started again, the freedom rights started.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
Well, they started, I think, in March.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:23.000
When it almost ended after the burning of the bus in Aniston, Alabama,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
several of us said, oh, I said, wait a minute.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
It's time we don't let this die.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:39.000
So we venture to Montgomery, Alabama to continue the ride from Montgomery to Jackson, Mississippi.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.000
And I don't know if you have seen the changing of the guard in Buckingham, Palace.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:49.000
But as they shifted from Alabama to Mississippi,

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:53.000
at least for 50 yards on either side of the highway,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:14:01.000
National Guardsmen, two state police cars in front, two behind in a helicopter flying overhead.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
We get to the state line,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:11.000
the bus stops on the opposite side on the Mississippi side.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:16.000
Two state police cars in front, two fell in behind,

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:22.000
and the helicopter, this time, obviously, the Mississippi National Guard or the Mississippi State Police,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:28.000
are shoving us into Jackson, Mississippi.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:36.000
I can only say that we didn't have time and didn't know at the time that a deal had been made

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
between the governor of Mississippi and Bobby Kennedy.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:46.000
This was when we were having a big problem with crew chef and the missile crisis and all the rest of it.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:53.000
You can't very well have the president of your country going talking about the duplicity,

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:58.000
if you will, of the people of Russia and yet here in America, you got the same problem.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:04.000
So the deal was cut that they would not allow us to be beaten,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
but we would be arrested immediately.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:13.000
And true enough, as soon as we stepped off the bus in Jackson,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
we were told to move on.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:20.000
And if we started for the white waiting room, you were under arrest.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
That's why this book, if I may, reached a piece.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
That was what the charge was.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:29.000
We were reaching the piece of Mississippi.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:38.000
Now, what did you think your relationship was at that point or what was your relationship with the president and with the attorney general?

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
You had no idea that this was going on in a closed door.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:47.000
Our salvation at the time was the cameraman, the newspaper reporters.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:53.000
We just thought that as long as they covered us, you know, the word would get out.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:16:00.000
And the pictures would get out just like the pictures of Rockwell over at Owington, Alexandria.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:01.000
You mentioned that before.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:06.000
I was going to follow up on that that, you know, you could get up in someone's face,

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:09.000
maybe when the cameras weren't rolling, when the camera was rolling,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.000
you're going to present something.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
So this was very conscious.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:16.000
You were courting the media and thinking about how this would play.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
Do you remember this conversation, sort of, again, that's another tactic.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
Do you remember those conversations planning this?

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:23.000
No.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:35.000
I had no, many people who went on the freedom route or engaged in sit-ins had, quote, non-violent training.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
My training was strictly on the job.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:45.000
And from my previous experience in Petersburg again, and then over to Virginia and England, I call.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:55.000
But I just knew that there was a no-win situation for me to, you know, try to start a fight.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:00.000
The people surrounding us outnumbered us.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:06.000
And back then, hey, I'm still way up 128 pounds.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:13.000
There's one picture that I don't know the date, but Jack Magazine had a photographer

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
by the name of Larry Still.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.000
And we were in Nashville picking a grocery chain.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
And I don't even recall the incident.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:27.000
But the picture that appeared in the magazine was a non-violent punch.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And it shows me of what purports to be me.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:36.000
Give it somebody a right cross.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
I don't know how I could forget that.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:45.000
And I'm just wondering whether or not that picture was really not of me, but just someone looking someone like me.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:49.000
But no, there were no discussions.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:59.000
We had a, I think, I don't know how long it lasted, but there was a guy who got a grant

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:05.000
to have a month-long seminar for quote, suffolite leaders.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:10.000
And I was fortunate enough to be selected to attend it.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:16.000
And we talked about stuff like philosophy, tactic, et cetera.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:25.000
And even then, you know, I was very vocal in terms of what I believed it to be as I've explained it somewhat already with you.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:33.000
I just can't imagine myself going through life turning the other cheek, if you will.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
So that's how that went in.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:40.000
And yet there were those moments where you were able to do that, even though it must have been very, very difficult.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
Oh, yeah, it was difficult.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:46.000
Again, I just knew that I represented more than me.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And if the picture got in the newspaper or on television, my hitting someone,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:19:01.000
whatever sympathies we might have had a good will, would be down the tube, and literally down the tube.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.000
So no, I mean, I was very aware of it.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:18.000
I'm not certain how much we actually coded the press, but I knew Don Well that there were times that I gave performances for the benefit of the press.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:23.000
And I restrained myself for the benefit of the cameras.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:26.000
So back to the freedom ride.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:30.000
Let's pick up where you were telling that story that we rest.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:44.000
Well, first of all, when we went, I was on the bus that arrived in Jackson on the very first day of the continuation of the ride.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:54.000
What I found interesting is that one bus pulled in, I think we were there an hour later.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:59.000
I don't recall now how many of us on that bus.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:05.000
But there were National Guardsmen with Bannets, you know, on Sheeves on the bus with us.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:11.000
So we used to think, or I used to think, naively, that, wow, we're being protected.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:27.000
What I didn't realize was, hey, these National Guardsmen until they were put on active duty with the same guys who were coming from out of their neighborhoods, cheering us and giving us holy hell.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:32.000
I just, it didn't register at any rate.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:39.000
When we arrived in Jackson and we were immediately arrested, we were thrown into the Hines County jail.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:42.000
It was almost like a drunk tank.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
We were all there collectively.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:52.000
And we didn't know that there were any other persons who would follow us.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:55.000
We just thought we were it.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:05.000
Then we were moved from the County jail a couple of days later to the County prison farm and from the prison farm to the state pinnit entry.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:12.000
And all the while, not knowing that the buses were continuing to come into town and coming to town.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:21.000
And what I was trying to explain previously, when people find out you were a freedom rider, they ask you, did you know so and so?

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:23.000
Who was also a freedom rider.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:33.000
And once we were arrested, let me tell you, white males were segregated from the black males, white females were segregated.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:37.000
So you didn't know everyone who was a freedom rider.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:44.000
You mainly knew the persons who were on the same bus that you were on or who got arrested at the same time.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:53.000
But it was weeks before we found out that the reason we were being moved was because they ran out of space.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:59.000
And it was interesting when they took us to the state pin.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:05.000
I was in the same, they put us at, it was called, I think, death row.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:08.000
But there were two people to a cell.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:15.000
You couldn't see who was in the cell next to you, but you only, you could talk.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:20.000
I shared a cell with Jim Fomer, who was then the director of CORE.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:28.000
And, you know, twice in life, well, perhaps more than twice, but twice in the civil rights movement.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:44.000
I have, I became somewhat humbled to be in a cell with Jim Fomer, and my supposedly being a leader at the local level and being as vociferous as I was.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:53.000
You know, there were times when I would ask Jim Fomer a question and I get a monosyllabolic response.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.000
And it was just quiet.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:59.000
And, you know, I was just humbled to be in the same cell.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:04.000
The second person that I actually occurred with was Bob Moses.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:11.000
Bob and I shared a house in McCone, Mississippi for some time.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:16.000
And the same thing was true.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:20.000
I couldn't stand being in the same movement and just being quiet.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:23.000
You know, I tried to strike a conversation.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:27.000
And, again, this mono response.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:33.000
But those were two people that I just felt humbled by.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:39.000
Yeah, it's, and the other thing about it is once again, talking about Petersburg, Virginia.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:49.000
Didn't realize it at the time, but Bob Moses had relatives in Petersburg that didn't know it until later we started talking.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:55.000
He's got cousins, he's got relatives, relatives, relatives.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:09.000
And it's just amazing how the intertwining, if you will, of people from disparate parts of the country ended up either in a cell or a picket line together.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:14.000
Who else did you know in the movement who had grown up in Petersburg?

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:20.000
And I was just wondering why I walked in to I think Cotton the whole gamut.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:30.000
And they had no influence whatsoever for my involvement because it happened post Petersburg.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:35.000
Because I never got arrested with those individual sittings that I had in Petersburg.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:39.000
And no one knew about it except for the people behind the counter.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:42.000
And there wasn't something that I went home and buried about.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:44.000
That's the other thing.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:48.000
Sometimes people ask me, well, what did your parents think about your involvement?

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:54.000
Or, many of the kids because they were under age had to have parental consent.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:59.000
Well, I have, like my leaving home at age 17, to go to New York to work.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:07.000
Who ever heard of a kid at that age going to work in a distant location for the summer?

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:10.000
Anyway, I've always been rather independent.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:15.000
I've always been somewhat of a leader.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:20.000
President of my high school, senior class, president, member of the student council,

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:23.000
president of the freshman class at Harvard, you know, the whole gamut.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:26.000
I've been somewhat independent.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:33.000
And I never had to ask for permission to do rid of the things that I did.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:39.000
When people asked what did your parents think, they didn't even know about it until it appeared.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.000
He didn't the newspaper or television or some reporter calling.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:46.000
And the same thing was true for several of the other artists.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:52.000
There's a minister from Virginia Union, not sure are, but his name is Reginald Green.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
And he's right here in DC also.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:26:00.000
And he said, my parents, his parents didn't know about it until a reporter knocked on the door.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
And informed them.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:08.000
And I guess to put it mildly, my parents were very proud of my involvement,

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:12.000
but they just wished it was someone else's child.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
I don't know.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:18.000
They wouldn't worry, right?

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:20.000
I guess we can...

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.000
Tell me about it.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:29.000
I've got a lot to cover, but we left you in prison.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:34.000
The first of many, I'm sure, from the Freedom Ride.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:37.000
Did you eventually...

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:39.000
Yeah, I can't play out that.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:42.000
I can say I go ahead and do that right.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:48.000
After losing that semester out of school, I thought I was going for a long weekend.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:51.000
The last two years have changed.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:27:00.000
When I got out of Punchman, I flew to Atlanta and said, well, let's see.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.000
The semester's gone.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:05.000
What can I do now that I'm already down here?

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:11.000
And they had this project in Mississippi, based in Pike County, where I admit,

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:20.000
the whole area around McComb, and that was my first assignment.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:24.000
So you had known some of the SNCC folks, but you had not formally been involved

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:28.000
when you, at the time, that you were doing the Freedom Ride, or were you already?

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:32.000
Well, because of my involvement in D.C., that made a connection.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:36.000
So, yes, I knew a few of you.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:44.000
Also, from that summer seminar retreat in Nashville, that's where I met most of the Nashville people.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:49.000
And there were quite a few, but there were other some other parts of the country.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:58.000
And I still don't know how that came about, because it was really a change moment.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:07.000
To meet the people who ended up in the newspaper, Diane Nash, Jim Bevel, Bernard Lafayette,

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:15.000
I met all of them before the Freedom Ride at any rate.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:21.000
It's amazing that the relationships that were formed have been lasting.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:26.000
I mean, here we are 50 some years later, and every time we see one another,

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.000
the Smithsonian has brought us together more than one occasion.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:36.000
This is my first trip with the Library of Congress, but when we've had these gatherings,

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:44.000
and especially the 50th anniversary, it's just amazing how we automatically just coalesced once again.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:51.000
And the other thing that was amazing, when we were arrested for the Freedom Ride,

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:55.000
there was not one African-American or the police force.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:59.000
There was not one African-American elected to public office.

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:03.000
So when I went back to McComb to do voter registration activity,

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:08.000
the thought was perhaps one day we might get a commissioner,

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:16.000
or we might get an elected official, never in our wildest dreams did we realize what we had unleashed.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Never thought about the person of color being in the US Congress or the US Senate.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:31.000
When we went back for the 53th Union, the mayor of Jackson, African-American,

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:39.000
the warden at the State Penitentiary, African-American female, and police force,

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:43.000
you know, I recognize now what happened. The town became gentrified.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:48.000
Not the other way around, I suppose I should say, the whites moved to the suburbs,

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:54.000
and the blacks became the majority. So that's how that transformation came about.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:30:00.000
But we did not realize that we'd have African-American congresspersons,

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:06.000
and most certainly hadn't given it a thought to an African-American president.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:12.000
Times have changed, but still there's a lot more to be done.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:17.000
And I don't know if it's on the Library of Congress or...

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:24.000
But somewhere downtown on one of the buildings, there's this Shakespearean phrase,

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:30.000
what is past is prologue. I think that's true.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:40.000
If you don't know your history, you should. You can very easily revert to what existed previously.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:44.000
And every time I give a presentation these days, I make it a point.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:50.000
Most people under the age of 35 today have no idea as to what the Civil Rights Movement was about,

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:56.000
what the freedom rise were about, and that's sad, because if the kids don't know,

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:00.000
we could very easily revert to what existed previously.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:07.000
And I try to make it a point. Education is indeed the most prominent way of clearing this up,

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:10.000
maintaining what we accomplished.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:15.000
19 and 1st got involved in this. Did you have a sense of what was at stake?

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:20.000
Did it feel like a choice to you, or did it feel like something that you had to do?

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:27.000
I think it's a ladder.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:31.000
I had no idea where it was going.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:38.000
I just knew that I wanted to make my contribution to make a difference.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:48.000
That might sound somewhat nebulous, because I'm not certain that I could have defined then what I was contributing to.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:54.000
I just knew I wanted to break down the barriers of segregation.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:32:02.000
I didn't have any long-range plans. I had no idea really what the outcome was going to be.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:13.000
Of course, if we were successful as we had been at Leneco, I'm sorry, at the lunch counter over in Virginia,

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:23.000
I had an idea that we could make a difference. We could bring about change.

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:29.000
You just bring back to McComb and take you back to that time.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:33.000
You went to Atlanta and got assigned to Mississippi.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:37.000
What was Mississippi like in 1961?

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:41.000
You were telling us about the change, but can you paint us a picture of what?

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.000
Oh, in 1961.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:47.000
You didn't get the chance to say, oh, you mean after I got out of jail?

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:53.000
I'm most certainly didn't see Mississippi, but Mississippi right now is a jail.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:33:04.000
I don't know how to describe it, other than the fact that it was worse than Petersburg.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:07.000
But it was also more fearful. I was more fearful.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:11.000
I was aware of the danger as opposed to Petersburg.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:16.000
The only thing that could have happened in Petersburg was white cop could have picked me up and taken me home.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:19.000
And said, hey, you're side of the town, so I'm raising you all.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:22.000
And which would have been true.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:27.000
But I mean, Mississippi, I was fearful.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:31.000
The other thing that's interesting is the house that I was in with Bob Moses,

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:34.000
the lady's name was, and that's name was cotton.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.000
We used to call it Mama Cotton.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:40.000
She was independent, had a house.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:50.000
And I don't know if you can gather this one, but the house had a two car garage.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:55.000
But where the doors for the two car garage might have been,

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:59.000
which transformed into a latisse window.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.000
Do you know what I mean by?

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.000
Just windowpains above, say, bed, bed level.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:09.000
My bed in this lady's house was parallel to this latisse window.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:17.000
At night, we just pulled the curtains and, like most southern towns,

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:21.000
persons of color lived near the railroad tracks.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:27.000
And almost every night around 11 o'clock, you could hear this free train going up a grade.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:33.000
And this one particular night, once again, remember, I had something like a 24-inch waist,

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:39.000
not like the present state of pregnancy that I'm now to see, look like.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:45.000
But a shotgun blast came straight through the window, passed over my body.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:51.000
Literally, if I would have had this girth then, a part of my body would have been shot off.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:35:01.000
But that really made me realize, yeah, the danger that we're in now.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:11.000
Unlike the stuff that happened after 61-62, Freedom Summer,

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:19.000
Bob Moses and Company up in the Delta, I got pulled out of, well,

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:26.000
I got sent to Holly Springs, Mississippi, from McCone,

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:31.000
and to do the very same thing, voter registration.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:38.000
Well, just after I'd gotten there, there was a guy by the name of E. Shelton Clock,

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:41.000
who was the president of Southern University.

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:47.000
Now, the kids in Baton Rouge had started having sit-ins.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:52.000
While I was at Holly Springs, the president closed the school

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:57.000
and kicked out a bunch of, quote, leaders.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:03.000
Well, Holly Springs is just a short jump from Baton Rouge.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:11.000
So I went over to Baton Rouge to get some of the kids who, school is closed,

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:14.000
this is almost like over the Christmas holiday period.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:19.000
To come back to Holly Springs to work with the unvoteer registration.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:24.000
But as soon as I get there, I've already called the bus company

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:30.000
to try to have a couple of buses to bring them to Holly Springs.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:36.000
Now, the fallacy that occurred,

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:40.000
while I was getting the kids organized to come to Holly Springs

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:46.000
and to go to Holly Springs, I hadn't arranged for any type of living quarters for them.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:52.000
But anyway, while I'm in Baton Rouge, the guy reopens the school

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:57.000
and everything that I was over there trying to do is down, down the tubes.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:03.000
When he reopened the school, he suspended.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:08.000
Several of the students who were supposed leaders.

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:12.000
So since everything had been wrecked,

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:17.000
I started organizing as a student on Baton Rouge's campus to boycott classes

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:24.000
until the president reinstated a lot of the quote, leaders.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.000
I think I was there for about four days,

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:31.000
going in and out of classroom buildings,

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.000
opening doors, telling people, come on, boycott, boycott.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.000
And with a very short two days, whatever.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:44.000
I somehow ended up in somewhat of a leadership role on a foreign campus.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:49.000
I mean, the people in Baton Rouge had never even heard of me prior to this activity.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:54.000
Well, I guess they figured they'd had enough of this.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:38:01.000
And they sent the state police, plus the campus police, to get me.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:03.000
And they got me.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:08.000
I was charged with trespassing, vacancy, disorderly conduct.

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:13.000
The main charge, those all misdemeanors.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:18.000
The main charge they got me on was criminal anarchy.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:21.000
They said I was attempting to overthrow the state of Louisiana.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:24.000
And in fact, that's true.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:25.000
I mean, I was.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:30.000
If you get enough people to vote, you can change the constitution and all the rest of the stuff.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:33.000
But then you rate them.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:40.000
Here's something that I didn't realize until Baton Rouge.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:47.000
Every time that I'd been arrested previously, it had been with a group of people.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:50.000
And there's safety in numbers.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:58.000
But when I got arrested in Baton Rouge, they flew me in a cell with the general population.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:04.000
And here's why that one stands out so much because one, I didn't know a soul.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:12.000
And at the East Baton Rouge Parish jail, if you're convicted of anything that's a misdemeanor,

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:18.000
you're thrown in the same cell block as someone who's already been convicted of murder,

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:22.000
but waiting for transportation to Angola or the state-pitted entry.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:31.000
And while in there, I saw a couple of kids who stole a car when you were riding on a weekend.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:36.000
And by the time Monday morning came around, they had been reaped.

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:41.000
And once again, I was a frail, skinny kid.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:47.000
And my voice was at least an octave higher than it is there.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:51.000
What was interesting about that was,

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:57.000
somehow the word got in that population that I was a freedom rider.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:03.000
Now, the term freedom rider became synonymous with civil rights worker.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:11.000
And when they found out what I was in there for, I gained a certain amount of respect.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:17.000
And the thing that was also interesting is that the white guards at toll once again,

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:21.000
it's all black male population.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:28.000
Had told them, hey, if you give them a rough time, we'll see if we can get you a time off a good behavior.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:34.000
So that's where I became really concerned.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:38.000
I mean, if you convicted a murder, you were in your way to the state-pitted for a long time.

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:41.000
You got nothing to lose.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:52.000
At any rate, when I did get a chance to talk to the local lawyer who represented the NAACP,

00:40:52.000 --> 00:41:00.000
somehow he was able to contact the FBI and they moved me to solitary confinement.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:08.000
Now, one thing I'm pleased with about myself, and I didn't find out until this particular time,

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:13.000
I can deal with solitary and my own solitary too very easily.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:19.000
But if you can imagine, I guess that cell was about eight feet by,

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:24.000
well, a square eight feet by six feet probably, at any rate.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:29.000
They would leave the lights on for 24 hours a day, but turned the lights out.

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:34.000
The only way I could tell the time of day, there's still going the middle of one with it,

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:40.000
but the stuff you see on TV, they would bring, I knew it was Saturday,

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:48.000
I knew Saturdays when they give you tours, give the general public tours of the jail.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:56.000
See that, Tommy? Girl Scouts, boy Scouts, just parading through and showing me off at any rate.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:03.000
The only way I could tell the time of day was breakfast was somewhere around 5'3''.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:08.000
Lunch was around 11'10' and 11'30' and dinner was around 4'''.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:14.000
That's how I could tell the time of day, but other than that,

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:18.000
I had my imagination to keep me going.

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:21.000
And, you know, I survived.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:32.000
I think when I got out of there, I've been in voter registration activities in Maryland,

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:39.000
I don't know if the name Gloria Richardson has come up in your travels,

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:48.000
but I'm now blocking for some reason this little town on the eastern shore of Maryland

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:53.000
and once again the local folks put me up in their homes and treated me most kindly

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:58.000
and we went about voter registration.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:01.000
It's been an interesting life.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:03.000
It most certainly has.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:09.000
You know, when you apply for a job, it used to be if you applied for a federal job,

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:14.000
and now it's almost if you apply for any job, they ask you have you ever been arrested.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:19.000
And with Tony and Cheek, I've been arrested approximately 30 times,

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:24.000
connection with civil rights activities. Please check with the FBI for dates and location.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:29.000
Because I most certainly don't remember all of them.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:38.000
But, you know, I think to to to to culminate this,

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:47.000
we were, excuse me, we were preparing for this is the years now, now 1963.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:54.000
We were trying to raise funds for sneak activity, voter registration activities.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:44:03.000
And I was sent to Columbus, Ohio to go to the annual Congress of the National Student Association,

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:12.000
which I said annuals for years, it's once a year, and we thought that we could get college campuses in the north

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:21.000
to get kids to volunteer for the following freedom summer and voter registration activities.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:28.000
I was standing next to a guy who was reading a newspaper, I was just looking over his shoulder,

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:35.000
I was seeing my college class was the class of 63.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:39.000
Kids were graduating and getting decent jobs.

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:45.000
And I said, wait a minute, I've been down here for two years and change.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:52.000
And I don't know why I said it out loud. I think it's time for me to get back in school.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:59.000
Well, I happened to be standing next to the guy who's a president of the student government at the University of Wisconsin.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:05.000
He said, would you consider coming to Wisconsin? I said, are you kidding?

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:13.000
Now, if you remember then, Berkeley and Auburn and Madison were the hot spots.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:22.000
This is August of 63. He says, don't move. He ran across the gymnasium floor that had been set up for the Congress,

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:28.000
came back with what I thought was a fairly elderly man, he must have been in the 30s.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:34.000
You know, back then, you obviously hit it at 30s, oh, at any rate.

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:40.000
This is late August. The guy asked me, he turned out to be the dean of students.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:46.000
I understand you might be interested in Wisconsin. I said, yes, he says, how are your grades?

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:52.000
I said, hey minus B plus, can you get a transcript? Yes.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:58.000
He said, get me a transcript. I went running to the newspaper, called the registrar at Harvard,

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:05.000
had my transcript forward into Wisconsin by the 9th of September when school started, I was enrolled.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:10.000
Now, you're talking about certain deputy. This was true to you.

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:16.000
I was a physics major at Harvard, but when I got to Wisconsin because of my civil rights activities,

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:22.000
I wanted to know, why did it take 50 years or approximately from the emancipation proc-

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:25.000
I mean, 100 years from the emancipation proc-

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:34.000
for there to be an organized protest. So I changed my major to history and sociology, civil war reconstruction.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:42.000
I still can't answer that question today.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:49.000
I guess it really takes a few folks with either stupidity or insight as a case maybe,

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:55.000
to just say, well, maybe if we do this, we can create change.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:47:02.000
That was my first serendipitous college transfer.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:12.000
In 1966, I came to DC to work for the local anti-poverty organization, the United Planet Organization.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:23.000
Back then, of course, that was when Johnson and all of the money was being poured into anti-poverty,

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:29.000
sod and shriver, and that group. I'd been working here until 1968.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:36.000
And one of the women that I worked with was working for OEO,

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:41.000
which was the National Office of Economic Opportunity, which funded the local groups.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:52.000
And I guess for some reason, she was impressed with the way that I worked with her.

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:59.000
And I'm almost certain this had some influence, but she said, D.I.,

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:09.000
would you be interested in going to Harvard? Now, are you talking about what I consider the silly question, of course.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:16.000
Well, I did a great, I ended up at Harvard.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:23.000
And once again, still trying to figure out what was the answer to that question,

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:36.000
I got into race relations and sociology. Still can't answer that question, but he is a funny part about Harvard.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:45.000
I'm almost certain that this was during the period of time when they were trying to diversify, you know, the student population.

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:52.000
I like to think it was also because I had grades, and I was deemed to be competent.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:49:01.000
But what surprised me at both Wisconsin and at Harvard, because this did not change,

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:11.000
it was Wisconsin, I think, out of about 18,000 students, they were less than 50 African Americans.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:19.000
And most of them were either on the basketball team or on the football team, you get my drift. They were athletes.

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:29.000
When I got to Harvard, oh, and the same thing, I'd sit in the class and I'd be the only personal color.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:46.000
And somehow they became aware of my civil rights activities, and they would look at the teachers, the profs would look at me for verification, as if, you know, I can speak for all persons of color.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:50:00.000
I got to Harvard. In several of my classes, you had to provide a resume in order for them to choose 15 students who they thought would make the best class.

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:09.000
In almost every case, I was the only African American in the class. And every time they would defer.

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:26.000
To me to verify something and call upon as you are interviewing me, call upon my civil rights experience and mind being a native silencer, to speak for, to ratify, justify how you were going to put it, you know, what they were teaching.

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:38.000
And I felt uncomfortable in that role. But by the same token, I was the only one in there who could either verify or refute.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:51.000
So I just assumed that role. The other thing about Harvard, I don't know how this is going to come across. I think the hardest thing about Harvard is to get in.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:51:01.000
Once you're in and you're able to show what you know and what you're capable of doing, it's very easy.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:11.000
And I made one mistake of many I think, but the biggest mistake I made at Harvard was almost the same when I made it Wisconsin.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:19.000
I didn't form any lifelong friendships.

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:28.000
I still relate to the kids I went to school for three semesters with at Harvard more so than, you know, anyone I went to school with at Harvard.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:39.000
I meet kids today who say, yeah, I got the Harvard. It was after you, but I heard about you. Yeah, I went to Harvard.

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:49.000
I guess again, this has been a heck of a trip. All in all, I would say, you know, it's been a good ride.

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:58.000
I was just going to say there was a lot to separate you from those other students, not just race obviously, but you had to live.

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:02.000
You know, and these were kids that you would been out there.

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:06.000
A lot of life experience can happen in a few years. Oh, that's true quite.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:12.000
It was a few years because only two years between Harvard, you know, in Wisconsin.

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:18.000
And only three years between Wisconsin and Harvard.

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:29.000
And I guess I was overwhelmed to be a student at Harvard.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:40.000
Many of the kids ended up at the business school. And then I bumped into people that I did not know were Harvard grads.

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:49.000
They said, yeah, we didn't go to the same school, but I knew you were on campus. Now that's a big campus.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:55.000
So I don't know. I mean, there's obviously a great fun. Oh, it was obviously a great fun.

00:52:55.000 --> 00:53:00.000
So what degree did you leave with that? My degree is in education.

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:10.000
Harvard has an agreement with MIT. I guess you call it a consortium.

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:19.000
Most of my classes were either in MIT or Harvard. Well, I guess basically those two.

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:29.000
And they were not, I think out of all of that, only one course through our recall as being at the grad school of education.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:38.000
That was indeed race and ethnic relations. That's what I did my thesis on.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:43.000
Yeah, it's, it's kind of wacky.

00:53:43.000 --> 00:54:01.000
I don't know how many people, I don't know how many people who experienced some of the stuff that I experienced have had the opportunity of these serendipitous, you know, segues, if you will.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:12.000
I know some kids who stayed at Harvard and graduated ended up going to an Ivy League business school, but they didn't have the civil rights experience that I had.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:22.000
And again, as I said in Columbus, Ohio, I got kind of peed when I found out my class was graduating in the head credentials that I had.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:27.000
It's time for me to get back in school.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:39.000
So I want to ask about what you did in your career after Harvard, but I want to dip back very quickly before we get too far away from it to one particular arrest and time in jail.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:45.000
And this was when I believe it was in Nashville when you were jailed along with Stoke Lee Carmichael.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:51.000
If I could ask about you know why I'm asking the story about this, but could I ask you to tell that?

00:54:51.000 --> 00:55:01.000
And by way of contrast to some of the first stories that you were telling about the lunch counter and walking quietly outside.

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:10.000
I think I have to disappoint you on that one mainly because the fact that that wasn't in Nashville, if I recall correctly.

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:15.000
I think that was supposedly at the state pit of entry in Mississippi.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:29.000
I may be wrong, but the reason I think I'm going to have to disappoint you is I have read and reread Stoke Lee's account of all being in that cell together.

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:34.000
And I can be the confirmed or deny that that occurred.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:42.000
I am capable of what he described. I guess for the record.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:51.000
I guess you really have to read it to appreciate it. Supposedly Stoke Lee and I were in the cell together. Supposedly this guard was halfway high.

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:55.000
Supposedly he was very odd and he had a shotgun.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:56:07.000
And according to Stoke Lee, I verbally engaged him and just just said go ahead shoot.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:17.000
I just don't remember that. I'm capable of it, especially as a ploy because I knew Darnwell.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:25.000
And Darnwell, there was no way he was going to kill us in a cell with all of the people in the block up and down.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:30.000
So I just, if I did, I just mouthed off.

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:34.000
But I would recognize it.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:40.000
When you let someone, you don't do it in a public view.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:47.000
If you're going to murder someone, you don't do it when you get a whole bunch of witnesses.

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:51.000
So that's the only way I could explain it.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:59.000
By that particular time, I've never been considered dumb.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:06.000
And I'm sorry if this is going to come about as a braggitassio.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:12.000
I've known since I was either a junior or a senior in high school what my IQ was.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:20.000
And the only reason I know that is because after we took the test, the teachers started pointing at me that diamond boy.

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:26.000
And I didn't know what I'd done because I'd be dying.

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:40.000
I can remember what I'd escalate when we were, I found out that supposedly my IQ is up there.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:53.000
But again, I didn't know why they were pointing at me at the time because previously we were to be given a standardized test.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:58:00.000
And the standardized, of course, means, of course, the country.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:16.000
I was frightened. I knew there would be no way for a kid to totally segregate a school to compete with white kids and black kids from all over the country on a standardized test.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:23.000
And this was to be a geometry exam.

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:30.000
And I couldn't fathom taking this test.

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:39.000
So my geometry class was just before, just before lunch.

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:46.000
Right next to my English class. So I unlocked the window.

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:51.000
You've got to picture this. My class was on the second story.

00:58:51.000 --> 00:59:06.000
There was an auto mechanic shop with a roof that was right at the step out of the window on the second level.

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:15.000
I threw a baseball out of the English class window onto the roof of the auto mechanic shop.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:20.000
We went out and mulled around and picked up the ball, but re-entered.

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:28.000
Or the makes-re-mover with a math class. I stole the standardized exam.

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:36.000
Now, the teacher's lounge is a couple of windows away. And they're just sitting there looking at me.

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:46.000
The math teacher knew what I had done. She gave me a zero on the final exam.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:53.000
I still passed the course because I had nothing but A's for the semester.

00:59:54.000 --> 01:00:06.000
Anyway, it was the worst thing I ever did, mainly because of the fact I aced it without having stole the standardized test.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:17.000
And that led me to understand that I underrated the teachers and the education I was getting in a segregated environment.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:26.000
And I think I've said this several times before. I think because in a segregated community, everybody knows one another.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:35.000
The teachers know your parents, your neighbors knew your parents. You could get a spanking between home and school or school and home.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:40.000
And it was just a given. I mean, it was understood.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:49.000
But I've said several times since then that we underrated the education that we got.

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:56.000
Because teachers just took more of an interest in you. And they talked to your parents more frequently.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:02.000
I don't know how valid that state it is, but I think that's about right.

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:05.000
So let me ask you then.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:09.000
By the way, I'm not suggesting I'm proud of what I just explained.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:11.000
No, I appreciate your candor.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:14.000
Just another thing in life.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:22.000
But at least we're going to ask this question about the obvious advances of the civil rights movement.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:28.000
And yet there are some things like desegregation of schools that could perhaps be seen as bittersweet.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:31.000
I agree with you on that.

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:35.000
I mean, based upon what I just said,

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:47.000
teachers don't take as much interest in the students today as they did in this small segregated community.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:53.000
It is bittersweet because teachers are underrated.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:02:05.000
I don't think with the way technology has advanced, teachers have the time to devote to students as they formally did.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:11.000
You know, you look at movies that depict school life today.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:13.000
I mean, it's kind of wild.

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:18.000
I don't know how you learn anything in an environment like that.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:24.000
Schools are now too big to be personal.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:33.000
I'm not certain how many teachers today really know anything about the home life of their students.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:37.000
And that makes a difference.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:52.000
Are there any other losses, do you think, that came along with the gains and so on?

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:59.000
Yeah.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:08.000
I think there's been a lack of the cohesiveness in forming friendships.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:15.000
You may say, well, what's the gotta do with anything?

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:28.000
I don't know if people have the binding friendships they had that they experienced in the segregated system.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:31.000
That's also related to my talking about the teachers.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:49.000
Maybe the fallacy of my logic is that I'm comparing small town, USA, with the big city.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:59.000
All of the civil rights experience from my high school education through my civil rights stuff,

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:08.000
were small town oriented, even in DC, when I got to go to Harvard.

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:10.000
It was relatively isolated.

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:15.000
It wasn't the big city, it was just that small campus.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:18.000
So you get closer to people.

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:32.000
Again, with the civil rights movement and how the colleges today have really grown in terms of student population.

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:41.000
Unless you're living in a dormitory, you really don't get a chance to interact.

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:46.000
I would say this.

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:58.000
I know at historically black schools, they call it HBCU's colleges and universities.

01:04:58.000 --> 01:05:06.000
They have been robbed of their most gifted athletes.

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:16.000
The big ten, all of your big schools have recruited the cream of the crop of athletes.

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:24.000
If you look at any professional football team these days, when they were not on the field and tell you where they went to school,

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:31.000
it's almost always a huge institution.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:39.000
The caliber of athletes that now go to historical black schools has decreased.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:45.000
Well, that's the social in educational aspect.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:53.000
Other than that, hey, we've made inroads, but I think the bit of sweetness again is

01:05:53.000 --> 01:06:05.000
that lots of us have forgotten from whence we came and don't recognize some of the barriers that still exist.

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:09.000
They're still, they talk about a glass ceiling for women.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:14.000
There's a glass ceiling for any person of color.

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:16.000
And I truly believe that.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:21.000
And then every time I say something like that, I look and see.

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:27.000
The president of American Express, or the CEO of American Express, African American.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:33.000
The president of the CEO of Hollywood American Cruise Line, African American.

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:39.000
So, you look at that and you say, wait a minute, you've made strides.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:43.000
Look at the rest of the infrastructure.

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:47.000
You've got one or two persons at the top.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:52.000
But how does that translate, you know, as you go through the ranks?

01:06:52.000 --> 01:07:02.000
I've not done a steady to verify what I'm saying.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:12.000
I get so confused today when I look at athletes who, athletes entertainers.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:26.000
I don't understand how this society can put such a premium on those persons as opposed to persons who are educated and persons who,

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:31.000
I feel like I've a better word.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:34.000
The intelligence here.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:46.000
Because we pay through the nose for guys who are fluent in no language, but can play football.

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:51.000
And how you find out after the fact that, well, they were making all that money and then they broke.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:08:01.000
I don't understand how people who hit the lottery or people who get paid these exorbitant salaries.

01:08:01.000 --> 01:08:10.000
Who can go out and buy five automobiles when they can only drive one, who buy two and three or four houses.

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:15.000
The next thing you know, so and so is broke.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:24.000
Well, I don't know where I was instilled with an appreciation for it.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:31.000
I don't want to say money, but that probably was what it was about.

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:37.000
I always see it growing older and being broke.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:44.000
I must admit, thankfully, that hasn't happened.

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:47.000
I don't know why I was instilled with that.

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:53.000
My parents were not well, they were about a long shot.

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:57.000
My dad was a male carrier.

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:02.000
My mom was a housewife until the kids were raised.

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:11.000
I had one older brother, then there's me and I'm the first one to get out of college.

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:15.000
I've got two siblings in the younger than I am.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:19.000
So we never had, you know.

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:24.000
In those days, a male carrier was equated the same as a school teacher.

01:09:24.000 --> 01:09:29.000
You get kids graduating from college and they become a school teacher.

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:34.000
You also had kids graduating from college who were going to be the male carrier.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:38.000
So they were like almost on the same plane.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:47.000
I can't say that I've been a Fugel, but I haven't been a spin-through.

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:53.000
I guess as you look around, you can say I'm not exactly poor living here.

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:56.000
Two questions, and maybe they're a little bit related.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:10:02.000
One is, if you could just tell us a little bit about your career going forward after you finished your education.

01:10:02.000 --> 01:10:11.000
The other question is sort of curious about we've met a number of SNCC people who are here in this area in the district

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:20.000
and I'm wondering about how people ended up here and whether those connections continued that you made during the movement.

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:25.000
I'll deal with the latter.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:30.000
Marion Barry is the reason so many of us are here.

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:34.000
If you recall, this used to be called Chocolate City.

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:47.000
And Marion, when he was mayor, bought more college graduates and SNCC people who ended up in professional positions in city government.

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:49.000
That's one of the reasons.

01:10:50.000 --> 01:10:57.000
As to whether or not the relationships that we forged back then still exist, they exist, but we don't socialize.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:11:08.000
It took the death of Julian Barr and the death of Marion for us to really just be together as a group.

01:11:08.000 --> 01:11:13.000
And you're right, there are quite a few of us here.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:20.000
Again, it's almost like you don't have to talk with someone in order to maintain a closeness.

01:11:20.000 --> 01:11:25.000
And I think that's true in this case.

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:29.000
In terms of my career,

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:36.000
it was a health of a skeleton.

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:40.000
Upon completing my education, I came back to DC

01:11:41.000 --> 01:11:49.000
and took a job as the US Department of Labor, my first job out of grad school.

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:56.000
And they had the same problem that some of the colleges had.

01:11:56.000 --> 01:12:02.000
They didn't have any African Americans of high enough rank.

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:16.000
And one of the shows you again, one of the women whom I met at Glen Echo had a father who was high up in the Labor Department.

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:21.000
And she introduced me to him and he introduced me to someone else.

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:27.000
And straight out of school, I ended up with a job that was a GS-14.

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:30.000
And I don't know if you know the government rankings.

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:35.000
That's pretty high.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:40.000
From there, I think I was at the Labor Department for about two years.

01:12:40.000 --> 01:12:50.000
And we went to a nonprofit that dealt with...

01:12:50.000 --> 01:12:55.000
I worked with training African Americans from all over the country,

01:12:55.000 --> 01:13:00.000
but mostly from the South, an economic development.

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:08.000
And many of those students back then whom we had, we trained at...

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:12.000
I was at Berkeley for an entire summer training.

01:13:12.000 --> 01:13:17.000
Some students from North Carolina, Durham, Chapel Hill, etc.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:27.000
who eventually went back to their hometowns and did economic activities, economic development activities.

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:34.000
After that job for about three years, I started my own consulting firm.

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:46.000
And between that and economic development activities and financial and analytical skills that were developed.

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:54.000
I've been a consultant to HUD, to HHS, what used to be HEW.

01:13:54.000 --> 01:14:01.000
And perhaps I can just tell you, at HUD it was again race and ethnic relations.

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:10.000
Dealing with segregated housing and how Black-Rand funds were being expended across the country.

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:15.000
From there, I went to HEW.

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:25.000
And I helped that design as a consultant, designing an instrument for determining fraud and abuse in the Medicaid Medicare program.

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:38.000
And we would design the and test it, this instrument all over the country, to find out how come some doctors and some dentists and some pharmacies

01:14:38.000 --> 01:14:43.000
would get away with a whole bunch of theft.

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:45.000
That worked.

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:55.000
Then I, again, with my consultancies, I did training for several of the agencies in the race and ethnic relations.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:15:01.000
Descending segregated patterns and how to have a more diverse clientele.

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:27.000
I, again, revered it to a job with the DC government in the Department of Housing and Community Development, writing grant applications to be funded by either HUD, or whenever I could pick up the money.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:35.000
I have been essentially a semi-retired for almost 15 years.

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:40.000
And I still have a couple of clients.

01:15:40.000 --> 01:15:43.000
I'm now 74 years old age.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:50.000
I still have a couple of clients that I deal with, guarding financial advisories.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:16:01.000
And when I say almost 15 years and 2008, when we had this financial collapse, I kind of collapsed.

01:16:01.000 --> 01:16:09.000
And I'm a leery now and I'm advising anyone on dealing with the stock market investments.

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:14.000
It's enough for me to try to hang on to what I've acquired.

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:24.000
And my spouse on the other hand, whom you met earlier, I cannot stand the thought of retirement.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:27.000
She continues to work and work.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:30.000
And I keep saying, hey, I thought retirement was going to allow us to travel.

01:16:30.000 --> 01:16:34.000
Well, we do travel, but not to the extent that I had in mind.

01:16:34.000 --> 01:16:37.000
I hope that answers your question.

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:51.000
So do you perceive, because I certainly do, but do you perceive a through line from civil rights movement through your work of focusing on reform efforts of various kinds?

01:16:51.000 --> 01:16:53.000
Well, let's put it this way.

01:16:53.000 --> 01:16:58.000
I'm certain had I not been in civil rights.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:01.000
I would not, well, three things.

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:09.000
Number one, I would have gone to Wisconsin, two, I would not have gone to Harvard, three.

01:17:09.000 --> 01:17:16.000
I don't think I would have the credentials that allow me to deal with racial issues.

01:17:16.000 --> 01:17:19.000
I would have been a physicist. I'm certain.

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:35.000
And this, you know, showed your home, my life has changed dramatically from being, you know, a technician or a scientist to being somewhat of a social scientist.

01:17:35.000 --> 01:17:41.000
Yeah, I mean, I don't love physics.

01:17:41.000 --> 01:17:50.000
I mean, I know the straight line that you're talking about, I don't know if it's straight, but it's never straight.

01:17:50.000 --> 01:18:04.000
Can I ask you, because of something that's personally curious to me interested in historically, is that period in the early 70s, I guess, in terms of black economic development, such that was such a crucial period and you were right right in there.

01:18:04.000 --> 01:18:21.000
Again, I don't, it's that line that you're talking about. One thing leads to another and I still feel that not enough emphasis is put on it.

01:18:21.000 --> 01:18:31.000
You know, people today, indeed, even me appreciated a job with an income as opposed to try to create income.

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:48.000
And I think that's the next hurdle. You know, most people today, irrespective of the race, you know, they really want a job that's going to pay a decent salary, put in the at 20 or 30 years and retire.

01:18:48.000 --> 01:18:53.000
I don't know if I was just reading Barron's magazine this morning.

01:18:53.000 --> 01:19:07.000
And well, that's the tech firms, the bonds upsellers. There's an article in the paper regarding how this guy got an $800 million bonus.

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:12.000
Can you imagine that? I mean, for making money at a wall speed brokerage.

01:19:12.000 --> 01:19:20.000
The tech guy who's the Facebook, he's giving all of his money to and that's a lot of them.

01:19:20.000 --> 01:19:28.000
But by the same token, I don't know if you follow Yahoo and the other tech firms that are now having problems.

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:37.000
The article suggests that it's a cycle. Tech firms get created, we make advances.

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:46.000
And then something else is created. And what the first firm has reached its plateau.

01:19:46.000 --> 01:20:01.000
So you got to keep creating wealth. And I don't know if enough people recognize that or don't feel comfortable trying to create, they just want safety and they want what?

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:10.000
I guess security is the word I'm looking for. Now, here's the way this one works.

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:19.000
When I was 19, people asked me how do I get it. What would I do the same thing over again?

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:29.000
If I knew then where I know now, probably not. But again, being age 19, not having a house note to pay.

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:36.000
Not having to put food on the table for anyone other than myself. Yeah, I would do that again.

01:20:36.000 --> 01:20:45.000
But with age, normally it comes responsibility. And responsibility can curtail a lot of what you can accomplish and what you end up.

01:20:46.000 --> 01:21:01.000
So again, I guess combine your question I eat. Would I would I do it again? And two is there a line that shows a progression in terms of how my life has has become?

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:14.000
Yeah, I is definitely there. But again, with economic development, someone has to keep creating wealth because, well, just does not stay the same.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:26.000
And as I said, in 2008, I made some bad choices. And I guess some of you can relate to that also.

01:21:26.000 --> 01:21:34.000
It's funny because when that occurred, my spouse had to me, well, do you know the way you play with this stuff?

01:21:34.000 --> 01:21:47.000
You make it back. And 2008 is what? Seven years ago. Well, guess what? I did make it back. But if it happened again, I don't have that much time left to make it.

01:21:47.000 --> 01:21:59.000
So that's why I become more fiscal, fiscally conservative. When people ask me, what are my politics? I say, oh, I'm a fiscal conservative.

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:07.000
So let me just ask you a few sort of more reflective questions as we get towards the end.

01:22:07.000 --> 01:22:09.000
Yeah, and I've gotten off the surprise beat. Right?

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:21.000
Yeah, so that's one thing I wanted to ask. And we've gotten added a little bit. But what do you think about where we are now and what sort of remains on the table?

01:22:21.000 --> 01:22:31.000
Well, I'll tell you personally, I'm disappointed in myself because I have become somewhat of a recluse.

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:45.000
I do nothing now to advance, you know, civil rights in America today. I do nothing to help kids start businesses.

01:22:45.000 --> 01:23:01.000
In fact, I guess I'm just out of it. And I think I still have something to offer. And I don't know why that I've become so satisfied, so complacent, so, well, you get my drift.

01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:16.000
But then too, when I look at many of my compatriots and also rights activists, they aren't either. You know, this stuff should be generational. It should keep progressing.

01:23:16.000 --> 01:23:27.000
And that's why I think I mentioned to you earlier, whenever I make a presentation, I try to instill some type of vigor in our youth.

01:23:27.000 --> 01:23:36.000
Because we are not at the same generation, and I really can't even relate to some of the stuff the kids today relate to.

01:23:36.000 --> 01:23:53.000
Everything for my choice of music. I don't even know how to use. I can use that computer, but I can't. I can't even use it on my phone.

01:23:53.000 --> 01:23:58.000
I purchased one a couple of weeks ago, and it's right up the other shelf.

01:23:58.000 --> 01:24:08.000
So, I don't know. I, again, I'm disappointed in myself in that I do no volunteer work and I should.

01:24:08.000 --> 01:24:23.000
But then too, when I say I shit, again, I get back to, I don't know how to provide any assistance to the youth because I can't relate to what they relate to.

01:24:23.000 --> 01:24:35.000
Does that answer you question? No, it's very much so. But when you see things like the, like just recently, you know, the Black Lives Matter campaign, you know, how do you respond to that?

01:24:35.000 --> 01:24:41.000
It shows obviously that there's still great need. But I'll just show you something.

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:45.000
Yeah, but you know something. Folks responding in some way.

01:24:46.000 --> 01:24:53.000
I'm not saying how my compatriots might respond to this response.

01:24:53.000 --> 01:25:13.000
I don't think there's anything to be gained by saying Black Lives Matter. Lives Matter. And until we get to a point where we see our relationship to one another, there's no need in just going back and saying, hey, Black, White.

01:25:13.000 --> 01:25:27.000
I mean, I think those distinctions should be made. But the point is, I see use the term Black Lives Matter kind of segments the issue.

01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:34.000
And I don't particularly relate to that.

01:25:35.000 --> 01:25:43.000
I think it follows this. When I see what happened in Charleston, I either.

01:25:43.000 --> 01:25:56.000
And I said, well, that kind of really shows where we are in this country. I mean, we still haven't, we still haven't cured the problem, if you will.

01:25:57.000 --> 01:26:08.000
And every time I hear Donald Trump, I don't mean to do, I do mean to get into politics.

01:26:08.000 --> 01:26:21.000
But here we are talking about putting barriers all over the country and keeping a particular ethnic or religious group from even coming here to visit.

01:26:22.000 --> 01:26:30.000
That bothers me quite a bit. But for my father's even more than what I find, I wish I could pull it out.

01:26:30.000 --> 01:26:39.000
The people who show up at Trump rallies, it kind of tells us something about where we are in the country. There are a whole bunch of people who don't vote.

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:49.000
There are a whole bunch of people who do vote. But if indeed, it's almost like a clan rally.

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:56.000
It kind of shows that we still have a long way to go.

01:26:56.000 --> 01:27:10.000
America is a hell of a lot better than it was in the past. And I must admit, every time I leave this country, whenever I get home, I always say, my God, I'm so glad I was born here.

01:27:10.000 --> 01:27:16.000
And that kind of sounds like a person is satisfied. But that's not what I'm trying to convey.

01:27:16.000 --> 01:27:28.000
This country has indeed come a long way into my knowledge. It's at the forefront of progress compared to other countries in the rest of the world.

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:35.000
And I think I've traveled rather extensively.

01:27:35.000 --> 01:27:42.000
I don't know. I mean, every now and then, when I turn on the C. Wait a U.K.

01:27:42.000 --> 01:27:51.000
The one that shows all the British programs. You look at Britain or the United Kingdom.

01:27:51.000 --> 01:28:03.000
And it looks as if it's a very integrated society. But recently, some racism is becoming apparent there also.

01:28:03.000 --> 01:28:10.000
So I don't know. I give accolades to America, but I say we still have a way to go.

01:28:10.000 --> 01:28:21.000
And I don't know. Every time, if you look around the South, you'll see a whole bunch of books on race and effort, relations and civil rights.

01:28:21.000 --> 01:28:29.000
And every time one of my comrades calls and say, hey, Dion, I'm trying to verify, so and so on. Do you remember?

01:28:29.000 --> 01:28:37.000
And I'll say, yeah, what my biggest regret is, I never kept notes. Because I could have written a book.

01:28:37.000 --> 01:28:51.000
But now, every time a book comes out, and this shows you, every time a book comes out, one of the first things I do is look at the back and see my name is in there.

01:28:51.000 --> 01:29:01.000
But I think that answers your question about a progress we've made and what I think of America. But it frightens me again.

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:19.000
What has passed is prolong. I mean, if we don't watch out, I mean, I'm proud of imagining not only if Trump could become president, if the things that he is professing or advocating would have come about,

01:29:19.000 --> 01:29:38.000
it's just frightening. And again, that's what has passed is prolong. He could make a whole past come back, put up a fence with Mexico and make them pay for it.

01:29:38.000 --> 01:29:47.000
You forget Ellis Island, right? What this country was based on, what it was made of.

01:29:47.000 --> 01:29:53.000
Okay, once again, I'm that grass. No, I don't think it's a that aggression at all.

01:29:53.000 --> 01:30:00.000
So I want to ask one final question, but I wanted to see if the folks behind the camera have any questions they'd like to contribute.

01:30:00.000 --> 01:30:05.000
I'm just cheering you on. I feel the same way.

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:10.000
Well, again, I didn't I didn't check with you first.

01:30:10.000 --> 01:30:15.000
Right. That's right. He's got some power.

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:27.000
So let me just ask the final question, which is there is there anything that I that you expected me to ask today that I should have asked for that I didn't ask that you'd like to address?

01:30:27.000 --> 01:30:35.000
No, I think you've got me talking again. I went a long way from civil rights.

01:30:35.000 --> 01:30:39.000
And again, I apologize for all of my verbal pauses, but

01:30:39.000 --> 01:30:54.000
what was your most memorable moment back from all those things that you can say that it capsulates my moment to the civil rights firm?

01:30:54.000 --> 01:31:06.000
Probably when the civil rights bill of 1964 was passed and

01:31:06.000 --> 01:31:16.000
to look at all of the elected officials who are now African-American, too.

01:31:16.000 --> 01:31:25.000
You know, one thing I didn't bring out and it was very fleeting in 1966.

01:31:25.000 --> 01:31:31.000
I'm sorry, 1968.

01:31:31.000 --> 01:31:43.000
I had been offered a job running the anti-poverty program out of the Marshall Islands.

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:48.000
Okay. I had been admitted to Harvard.

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:54.000
And I got a job working on Bobbi Kennedy's campaign.

01:31:54.000 --> 01:32:06.000
And I had three options. One, I figured if I were to go out to the Marshall Islands and Micronesia.

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:11.000
Even though they said you can come home once a year and you only 90 miles from Japan or something like that,

01:32:11.000 --> 01:32:18.000
I figured that probably ended up marrying some Micronesian woman and I'd never get back to the States.

01:32:18.000 --> 01:32:29.000
The other thing was I said, well, if Bobbi Kennedy's elected president, I might end up with the job in the White House.

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:34.000
And I said, if none of this stuff falls out, I still got Harvard in the hole.

01:32:34.000 --> 01:32:41.000
Well, you know what happened? I didn't go to Micronesia. Bobbi Kennedy got killed and I ended up at Harvard.

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:48.000
Now, all of these things, I pay the hell of a mosaic.

01:32:48.000 --> 01:32:58.000
I don't say that regularly. I'm meaning me that most people have not had the experiences that I've had.

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:07.000
And again, it was civil rights that got me into this way, the way I...

01:33:07.000 --> 01:33:10.000
And I have benefited, obviously.

01:33:10.000 --> 01:33:27.000
And I think the Civil Rights Act and the election of Obama have to be the highlights.

01:33:27.000 --> 01:33:32.000
Because again, who the heck expect...

01:33:32.000 --> 01:33:40.000
You expected Jack Kennedy to do something in connection with Civil Rights.

01:33:40.000 --> 01:33:50.000
You never expected Lyndon Johnson or Southerner to be the guy to implement it.

01:33:50.000 --> 01:33:58.000
I never expected to see the elected officials at the level that has occurred.

01:33:58.000 --> 01:34:04.000
I hope that answers your question. I mean, that covers a hell of a period of time.

01:34:04.000 --> 01:34:15.000
But nevertheless, all of it had its roots, if you will, and my participation in the movement.

01:34:15.000 --> 01:34:19.000
Best I can do.

01:34:20.000 --> 01:34:25.000
Thank you so much. That was terrific.

01:34:25.000 --> 01:34:34.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

